#compdef mathics mathics3
# =============================================================================
# mathics — Mathics3's open-source Wolfram Language kernel — a
#            free reimplementation of Stephen Wolfram's Mathematica
#            in Python.  Implements the Wolfram Language
#            programming environment with symbolic math, pattern
#            matching, functional programming primitives, and an
#            interactive REPL.  Mathics3 covers a substantial
#            subset of Mathematica's built-in functions:
#              - Symbolic algebra: Solve, Simplify, Expand, Factor,
#                Apart, Cancel, PolynomialDivision
#              - Calculus: D, Integrate, Limit, Series, Sum,
#                Product
#              - Linear algebra: MatrixPower, Eigenvalues,
#                Eigenvectors, Inverse, Det, LinearSolve
#              - Pattern matching: Cases, MatchQ, ReplaceAll,
#                ReplaceRepeated
#              - Functional programming: Map, Apply, Fold, FixedPoint,
#                NestList, Function (& and # syntax)
#              - List operations: Table, Range, Reverse, Sort, Union,
#                Intersection
#              - I/O: Print, ToString, ToExpression, Import, Export
#              - Plotting via matplotlib (Plot, Plot3D, ListPlot,
#                ContourPlot, etc.)
#            Designed as a drop-in Wolfram Language interpreter for
#            users who don't want / can't license commercial
#            Mathematica.  Used in academic research, math education,
#            and as a testing reference for Wolfram Language code
#            that needs FOSS portability.
#
# Author:  Mathics3 Group (mathics-devel@googlegroups.com) — lead
#          developer Rocky Bernstein (also creator of trepan3k Python
#          debugger).  Originally created by Jan Pöschko in 2011 at
#          mathics.org, forked to Mathics3 organization in 2021.
# Source:  https://github.com/Mathics3/mathics-core
# CLI:     mathics/__main__.py (uses Python stdlib argparse with
#                                 MULTI-NAME alias support — each
#                                 add_argument call registers multiple
#                                 names for the same argument:
#                                 `add_argument("--help", "-help", "-h"
#                                 ...)` lets users use any of the three
#                                 forms, matching Wolfram Mathematica's
#                                 own command-line conventions where
#                                 single-dash `-help` is the canonical
#                                 form)
# Library: Python stdlib `argparse` with MULTI-NAME ALIAS REGISTRATION
#          (each add_argument call accepts 1-N option strings; argparse
#           routes any of them to the same destination.  This is
#           STANDARD argparse but used UNUSUALLY by Mathics — most
#           argparse users register 1-2 names per argument; Mathics
#           registers 3+ to preserve Wolfram Language convention.)
