#
# WHAT IS WOLFRAM LANGUAGE AND WHY IS IT THE 70TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Wolfram Language (https://www.wolfram.com/language/) is **Stephen
# Wolfram's symbolic-computation programming language** — created in
# 1988 as the language of Mathematica, renamed to "Wolfram Language"
# in 2013 to emphasize its independent identity from the Mathematica
# product.  Wolfram Mathematica is the canonical commercial
# implementation; Mathics3 (https://github.com/Mathics3/mathics-core,
# 1179+ stars) is the de-facto open-source implementation.
#
# Wolfram Language's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. EVERYTHING IS AN EXPRESSION — Wolfram Language programs are
#      built from EXPRESSIONS — tree structures with a head (the
#      operator/function) and a list of elements:
#
#          Plus[1, 2, 3]         (* equivalent to 1 + 2 + 3 *)
#          Times[x, Power[y, 2]] (* equivalent to x * y^2 *)
#          If[x > 0, Sqrt[x], -Sqrt[-x]] (* function call *)
#          List[1, 2, 3]         (* equivalent to {1, 2, 3} *)
#          Rule[x, 5]            (* equivalent to x -> 5 *)
#          Pattern[name, _]      (* equivalent to name_ *)
#
#      Even infix operators (`+`, `*`, `==`, `->`) are SUGAR for
#      Head[Args...] form.  Compare:
#         * Lisp: similarly expression-everything but with quote
#                   semantics (Wolfram has Hold semantics instead)
#         * Mathematica/Maple/MuPAD: similar symbolic CAS
#         * Wolfram Language is the most ADOPTED symbolic-CAS
#           language with active commercial+academic ecosystem
#      FIRST documented expression-everything symbolic-CAS language
#      in the taxonomy.
#
#   2. PATTERN MATCHING AS PRIMARY EVALUATION MECHANISM — Wolfram
#      Language's evaluator continuously applies pattern-matching
#      rewrite rules to expressions until they reach canonical
#      form.  Pattern syntax:
#
#          f[x_] := x^2 + 1           (* f[anything] becomes its
#                                         argument squared plus 1 *)
#          g[x_Integer] := "int"      (* g[integer] specifically *)
#          h[x_, y__] := x + y        (* x_ matches one, y__
#                                         matches one-or-more *)
#          i[a_ -> b_] := b -> a      (* matches Rule[a,b] *)
#          Cases[{1, a, 2, b, 3, c},
#                _Integer]            (* returns {1, 2, 3} *)
#          Replace[expr, x_^2 :> y]   (* replaces x^2 patterns *)
#
#      Patterns can include blank (`_`), typed blank (`_Integer`),
#      named blank (`x_`), sequence blank (`__`, `___`), conditional
#      (`/;`), with-context (`/.`).  Compare:
#         * Haskell:  pattern matching but only on data constructors
#                      at function definition; no rewrite rules
#         * OCaml:    similar to Haskell
#         * Erlang:   pattern matching on data + guards
#         * Wolfram:  pattern matching on ARBITRARY EXPRESSIONS with
#                      rewrite-rule evaluation
#      FIRST documented language with pattern-matching rewrite
#      rules as the PRIMARY evaluation model.
#
#   3. MASSIVE BUILT-IN FUNCTION LIBRARY — Wolfram Language has
#      6000+ built-in functions covering:
#         * Symbolic math (Solve, Simplify, Expand, Factor)
#         * Calculus (D, Integrate, Limit, Series)
#         * Linear algebra (MatrixPower, Eigenvalues, Inverse)
#         * Number theory (PrimeQ, FactorInteger, Mod)
#         * Probability (Probability, RandomVariate, Distribution)
#         * Statistics (Mean, Variance, FitModel)
#         * Plotting (Plot, Plot3D, ContourPlot, ListPlot)
#         * Image processing (ImageResize, ImageFilter, FaceDetect)
#         * Graph theory (Graph, FindShortestPath, GraphPlot)
#         * Machine learning (Classify, Predict, NetGraph)
#         * Natural language (Interpreter, SemanticImport)
#         * Curated data (WolframData, CountryData, ChemicalData)
#         * Geographic (GeoGraphics, GeoDistance, City)
#      Mathics3 implements ~1500 of these (the most commonly used).
#      Compare every other documented language — Python's standard
#      library is ~500 modules; Wolfram has 6000+ built-in
#      functions.  LARGEST built-in function library of any
#      documented language.
#
#   4. NOTEBOOK FORMAT — Wolfram Language's primary IDE is the
#      Mathematica Notebook (.nb files): a structured document
#      combining code cells, formatted text cells, equation cells,
#      plot cells, and table cells.  Notebooks predate Jupyter by
#      ~25 years (Mathematica notebooks: 1988; Jupyter: 2014).
#      Wolfram notebooks support inline output (no need to print —
#      the last expression of a cell auto-displays), rich
#      typography (TraditionalForm), interactive widgets (Manipulate),
#      and cross-cell variable persistence.  Mathics3 includes
#      mathicsscript (a richer REPL than mathics) but doesn't ship
#      a notebook interface (use mathics-django for web-notebook
#      access).
#
#   5. INFINITE-PRECISION ARITHMETIC BY DEFAULT — Wolfram Language
#      uses arbitrary-precision integers and rationals by default:
#
#          2^100                         (* gives exact
#                                            1267650600228229401496703205376 *)
#          1/3 + 1/4                     (* gives 7/12, not 0.583333... *)
#          Sqrt[2]                       (* stays symbolic as Sqrt[2],
#                                            not 1.41421... *)
#          N[Sqrt[2], 50]                (* converts to 50-digit
#                                            precision: 1.4142135623730...
#                                            *)
#          N[Pi^Pi^Pi, 100]              (* 100-digit decimal expansion
#                                            of Pi^Pi^Pi *)
#
#      Compare:
#         * Python: int is arbitrary-precision; float is fixed
#                    IEEE 754; Decimal class for arbitrary-precision
#                    decimals
#         * Common Lisp / Scheme: bignums + ratios built-in
#         * Wolfram: NUMBERS STAY SYMBOLIC until explicitly
#                     numericalized via N[expr, digits]
#      Mathics3 inherits Wolfram's arbitrary-precision semantics
#      via Python's mpmath library.
#
# Wolfram Language's relationship to other documented languages:
#
#   * Like Lisp / Scheme / Racket — homoiconic + expression-based
#   * Like Coq / Idris / Lean      — symbolic-CAS aspects of proof
#                                     assistants
#   * Like Haskell                  — strong pattern matching
#   * Like Erlang                   — pattern-based function definition
#   * Like Mathematica's predecessor LISP-based CAS (Macsyma 1971,
#     Maxima derived from it) — same CAS lineage
#   * Unlike all of the above — combines pattern-matching rewrite
#     rules + arbitrary-precision arithmetic + 6000+ built-in
#     functions + symbolic-everything + notebook-first IDE in ONE
#     integrated environment.  Wolfram Language is the most
#     COMMERCIAL-MATURE symbolic-CAS environment (Wolfram Inc has
#     been continuously developing Mathematica since 1988).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE mathics CLI — Python stdlib argparse with Multi-Name Aliases
#
# Mathics's argv parser is Python stdlib `argparse` configured with
# MULTI-NAME aliases per argument:
#
#     argparser = argparse.ArgumentParser(
#         prog="mathics",
#         usage="%(prog)s [options] [FILE]",
#         description="A general-purpose computer algebra system.",
#     )
#     argparser.add_argument("-f", "-file", "--file", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--help", "-help", "-h", action="help")
#     argparser.add_argument("--full-form", "-F", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--initfile", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--persist", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--pyextensions", "-l", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--quiet", "-q", action="store_true")
#     argparser.add_argument("-script", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--code", "-code", "-c", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--cprofile", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--colors", nargs="?")
#     argparser.add_argument("--no-completion", action="store_true")
#     argparser.add_argument("--no-readline", action="store_true")
#     argparser.add_argument("--version", "-v", action="version")
#     argparser.add_argument("--strict-wl-output", ...)
#     argparser.add_argument("--trace-builtins", "-T", action="store_true")
#     argparser.add_argument("--show-statistics", action="store_true")
#
# Every flag has BOTH long-form `--name` AND Wolfram-convention
# `-name` (single-dash) AND short `-x` aliases.  This is a
# DELIBERATE choice to support users who learned Wolfram Language
# from Mathematica's command-line conventions (single-dash) AND
# users from POSIX/GNU conventions (double-dash).
#
# Distinct from every other documented argparse-using CLI on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. MULTI-NAME ALIAS REGISTRATION — Every other documented
#      argparse usage registers 1-2 names per argument (typical
#      `--long, -s`).  Mathics registers 3+ names per argument to
#      preserve Wolfram Language single-dash convention alongside
#      POSIX double-dash:  `--help`, `-help`, `-h` all map to the
#      same destination.  FIRST documented argparse usage with 3+
#      aliases per argument.
#
#   2. WOLFRAM-CONVENTION SINGLE-DASH LONG OPTIONS — Every other
#      documented CLI library uses POSIX/GNU convention: single-
#      dash = short flag (one char), double-dash = long flag.
#      Wolfram Mathematica historically used single-dash for ALL
#      flags including long ones (`-script`, `-help`, `-code`).
#      Mathics preserves this Wolfram convention while ALSO
#      accepting POSIX double-dash forms.  FIRST documented CLI
#      library that supports both POSIX and Wolfram-Mathematica
#      conventions simultaneously.
#
#   3. SYMBOLIC-EXPRESSION INPUT VIA -code/--code — Mathics's
#      `-code "expr"` flag evaluates a Wolfram Language expression
#      directly without entering the REPL.  The expression is
#      parsed by the full Wolfram parser (including infix operators,
#      pattern syntax, replacement rules).  Compare every other
#      documented CLI library — none have a flag that takes a
#      SYMBOLIC EXPRESSION in the language's own syntax.  FIRST
#      documented CLI library with symbolic-expression-as-flag-
#      value support.
#
#   4. TRACE-BUILTINS DEBUG MODE — `--trace-builtins` (or `-T`)
#      enables tracing of EVERY builtin function call during
#      evaluation.  Useful for debugging pattern-rewrite chains
#      that produce unexpected results.  Compare every other
#      documented CLI library — none have flag for tracing
#      INTRINSIC operations.  FIRST documented CLI library with
#      builtin-function-tracing flag.
#
#   5. SHOW-STATISTICS LRU-CACHE INSPECTION — `--show-statistics`
#      prints LRU-cache hit/miss statistics for Mathics's
#      memoization caches (built-in function results are cached
#      to speed up repeated calls).  This exposes implementation-
#      internal performance metrics via a CLI flag.  FIRST
#      documented CLI library with cache-statistics inspection
#      flag.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/Mathics3/mathics-core/blob/master/mathics/__main__.py
# argparse `add_argument` calls in `main()` function.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(--help -help -h)'{--help,-help,-h}'[show this help message and exit]' \
    '(--version -v)'{--version,-v}'[show version information and exit]' \
    '(-f -file --file)'{-f+,-file=,--file=}'[execute Wolfram Language code from this file]:file:_files -g "*.(m|wl|nb)"' \
    '(--initfile)--initfile=[same as FILE and --persist together]:file:_files -g "*.(m|wl)"' \
    '(--persist)--persist[go to interactive shell after evaluating FILE or -e]' \
    '(--post-mortem)--post-mortem[go to post-mortem debug on terminating system exception (needs trepan3k)]' \
    '(-script)-script[run a mathics file in script mode]' \
    '(--code -code -c)'{--code=,-code=,-c+}'[execute a Wolfram Language expression and exit]:expression:' \
    '(--full-form -F)'{--full-form,-F}'[show FullForm of input and output]' \
    '(--quiet -q)'{--quiet,-q}'[do not print message at startup]' \
    '(--colors)--colors=[color scheme]:scheme:(NoColor DarkBG LightBG Linux)' \
    '(--no-completion)--no-completion[disable tab completion]' \
    '(--no-readline)--no-readline[disable readline support]' \
    '(--pyextensions -l)'{--pyextensions=,-l+}'[additional Python extension modules to load]:module:' \
    '(--cprofile)--cprofile[run cProfile on --execute argument]' \
    '(--strict-wl-output)--strict-wl-output[strict Wolfram Language output format]' \
    '(--trace-builtins -T)'{--trace-builtins,-T}'[enable tracing of builtin function calls]' \
    '(--show-statistics)--show-statistics[print LRU-cache hit/miss statistics on exit]' \
    '*:Wolfram Language file:_files -g "*.(m|wl|nb)"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
